        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              A recent UK-China Transparency report, based on a broad survey of
              academics within the field, warns that China Studies in British
              universities are in crisis. Source: BBC News</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Chinese students at UK universities were
            pressured by Beijing to
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-aug-25-spotlight-h1-1-monitor-their-classmates"
              target="_blank"
              >monitor their classmates</a
            >, and lecturers were restricted from discussing sensitive topics.
            The researchers were denied visas, and family members back in China
            were harassed. Academics reported intimidation by visiting scholars
            or other Chinese officials and by staff from Confucius Institutes
            (Chinese NGO). The Chinese embassy in London has rejected the
            accusations.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The background:</strong> The UK unveiled the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-aug-25-spotlight-h1-2-latest-legislation"
              target="_blank"
              >latest legislation</a
            >
            on freedom of speech on academic grounds. It requires universities
            to promote robust discussion without the fear of censorship of
            students, staff, or external speakers. Universities will be banned
            from using non-disclosure agreements to silence victims of campus
            misconduct. The Office for Students (OfS) can investigate and
            intervene if universities fail to protect speech rights.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The reaction:</strong> The OfS said that universities could
            face heavy fines if speech rights are not protected. Universities
            UK, which represents 141 institutions, said it will work closely
            with the government to protect students. Earlier this year, the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-aug-25-spotlight-h1-3-ofs-imposed-a-7-7m-fine"
              target="_blank"
              >OfS imposed a $7.7M fine</a
            >, underscoring the government’s firm stance on the matter.
          </p>
