          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong
              >Summary: Syria’s upcoming parliamentary vote is raising fears of
              sectarian violence in minority regions.</strong
            >
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Syria is set to hold
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-aug-25-analysis-h1-8-parliamentary-elections-in-mid-september"
              target="_blank"
              >parliamentary elections in mid-September</a
            >, the first since the fall of the Assad regime. The parliament will
            consist of 210 members: 140 to be elected and 70 appointed by
            interim President Ahmed al-Sharaa. This vote is part of a
            transitional process intended to lead to a revised constitution
            within three years. While the elections mark a significant political
            milestone, the broader national context remains deeply unstable.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The concerns:</strong> Violence overshadows the elections,
            especially in minority areas. Recently, deadly unrest
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-aug-25-analysis-h1-9-hit-the-druze-majority"
              target="_blank"
              >hit the Druze-majority</a
            >
            Sweida. While an agreement was made in March, Kurdish regions are
            still tense and heavily armed. Activists warn that al-Sharaa's
            control over 70 parliamentary appointments might strengthen his
            inner circle instead of including marginalized groups.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The impact:</strong> The outcome of these elections will
            shape Syria’s political future. If the process is seen as fair and
            inclusive, it could boost national unity. But if it is ruled by
            sectarian politics or viewed as a power grab, it may deepen
            divisions and hurt hopes for lasting stability.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
