            What was the Roma Holocaust?
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image
          border-radius="10px"
          padding="10px 12px"
          width="600px"
          src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/roma-holocaust-memorial-germany.jpg"
          alt="A man stands in front of a memorial adorned with wreaths and flowers, with a banner in German referencing the persecution of Roma people from Auschwitz to the present day."
          href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com"
        />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              2025 marks the 81st anniversary of 2 August, the European
              Holocaust Memorial Day for Sinti and Roma. Source: Friedrich
              Stark/Alamy via History Today
            </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Between 1933 and 1945, Nazi Germany
            targeted Roma and Sinti communities across Europe in a campaign of
            racial persecution that
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-aug-25-foundations-h1-16-escalated-into-genocide"
              target="_blank"
              >escalated into genocide</a
            >. Early measures included police surveillance and forced
            sterilizations under
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-aug-25-foundations-h1-17-nazi-eugenics-laws"
              target="_blank"
              >Nazi eugenics laws</a
            >. Later, the Nuremberg Laws stripped them of citizenship and civil
            rights. Classified as a racial threat, they faced state-sponsored
            “research” aimed at isolating and exterminating them.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The violence:</strong> Violence against Roma was widespread
            and brutal. Many were murdered in mass shootings by Einsatzgruppen
            (SS death squads) or died in ghettos and camps from disease,
            starvation, and forced labor. In Auschwitz-Birkenau, over 19,000
            Roma were killed in the gas chambers and inhumane experiments. On
            August 2, 1944, Roma prisoners in the "<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-aug-25-foundations-h1-18-gypsy-family-camp"
              target="_blank"
              >Gypsy Family Camp</a
            >" at Auschwitz tried to resist, but the revolt was crushed with
            mass executions.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The aftermath:</strong> Known as Porajmos (meaning "the
            Devouring"), the Roma genocide was ignored for decades. Survivors
            faced continued discrimination after the war, and formal recognition
            came decades later. The EU now marks August 2 as
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-5-aug-25-foundations-h1-19-european-roma-holocaust-memorial-day"
              target="_blank"
              >European Roma Holocaust Memorial Day</a
            >, while they still face significant social and economic
            discrimination.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Clarification:</strong> “Roma” refers to the Romani people,
            not the city of Rome, and replaces the outdated and offensive term
            “Gypsy.”
          </p>
